IMF needs more Lagarde
At Davos, Lagarde once said she would be open to serving another five years as the head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should be reappointed.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than hers, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting an institution plagued by crises.
The 2008 global financial crisis and its economic aftermath severely damaged the credibility of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the "Washington Consensus" of free market ideology.
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF regain its reputation.
Many eyes were on her personal qualities - and rightly so.
She was candid, strong, warm, and inspiring.
Government officials from various countries (often in delicate situations) who met with her consistently praised her for being able to express difficult realities while also being a sensitive listener.
For an institution leader who must negotiate terms rather than dictate everything, these are important qualities.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, otherwise a firewall would have to be built to prevent financial contagion. Her words fell on deaf ears, but Europeans still went ahead.
Similarly, she loudly advocated for IMF support for certain countries — Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples like this.
The IMF is not good at innovation and is usually not passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
In this process, she gave the institution, which often prescribed harsh remedies, a humanitarian face.
For example, helping to manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not originally within the IMF's sphere of responsibility.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans, allowing the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to help refugees affected by the Syrian and Iraqi conflicts (over a million refugees lived in camps within Jordan's borders).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola epidemic broke out in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in providing debt relief to crisis-hit countries using callable funds, enabling them to improve the salaries of doctors and nurses – this was the IMF's first use of its capital for such a purpose.
Moreover, Lagarde recognizes that the world is facing three major challenges today and takes action against them.
Firstly, she strongly advocates for more women to join the workforce, serving as a role model herself as a woman in a leadership position.
In various countries from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urges leaders to stop wasting such a vast amount of human talent — and thereby unlock economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addresses the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic fairness issue.
The IMF's research emphasizes a direct link between reducing income inequality and increasing economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to prove this point, but its prominent position makes this issue more pressing and urgent.
Lagarde has personally been committed to promoting this point, which is crucial in raising its urgency.
Thirdly, Lagarde has played an important role in helping the world understand the full impact of technological change – some of which will have frighteningly destructive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase the efficiency and lower the costs of manufacturing, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be fewer than before.
This new reality's political, economic, and social consequences are worth acknowledging and seriously studying.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this work.
Critics will say it's time for developing country representatives to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe has had such privilege that it's hard to please the world today.
Some will also say that the IMF-backed Greek austerity measures did not have a full effect, proving that she has become disconnected from the ordinary public.
Some people also point out that she faces allegations related to the French financial scandal, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn became embroiled in a scandal, critics argued that the IMF could not afford to be distracted again by a similar incident.
Let's analyze these opposing views one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the US.
The goal of ending this Western privilege is to make the leader selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice for IMF president, and emerging powers such as the BRICS nations (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) did not jointly nominate an alternative candidate.
Having an European as IMF president may also have been a factor in the IMF's decision last year to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies that determine the value of its special drawing rights.
Moreover, Lagarde's impressive political flexibility ultimately convinced both the Republican and Democratic parties in the US Congress to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal to combat financial crises but also better reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS nations are now among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, Lagarde made some comments last year that were both personal and direct – some people thought them inappropriate –.
But she is not the one who brought economic pain to the Greeks; during her term at the IMF, she has done more than any other president in IMF history to lead the IMF's efforts to alleviate the suffering of the people in the midst of crises.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde by France were opposed by the French prosecutor general, and Lagarde was at most only marginally involved.
The world needs a leader who is committed to making the world a safer and more prosperous place.
Lagarde has proven herself to be such a leader, committed to making the IMF relevant in the 21st century.
She should be given the opportunity to see her work through to completion.
